{"@context":"http://iiif.io/api/presentation/3/context.json","id":"https://digbmc.github.io/pta-manifests/phan/phan-04918/manifest.json","type":"Manifest","label":{"none":["PHAN-04918"]},"metadata":[{"label":{"none":["Timestamp"]},"value":{"none":["0:49:18"]}},{"label":{"none":["Film"]},"value":{"none":["Phantom Thread"]}},{"label":{"none":["Creator"]},"value":{"none":["Paul Thomas Anderson"]}},{"label":{"none":["Distance"]},"value":{"none":["close-up"]}},{"label":{"none":["Angle"]},"value":{"none":["eye-level"]}},{"label":{"none":["Location"]},"value":{"none":["interior"]}},{"label":{"none":["Movement"]},"value":{"none":["mobile, handheld, pan"]}},{"label":{"none":["Composition"]},"value":{"none":["single shot"]}}],"summary":{"none":["A man stares at a woman offscreen."]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04918/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"homepage":[{"id":"PHAN-04918","type":"Text","format":"text/html","label":{"none":["Object homepage"]}}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04918/canvas/1","type":"Canvas","height":1080,"width":1920,"label":{"none":["PHAN-04918"]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04918/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04918/canvas/1/annopage-1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04918/canvas/1/annopage-1/anno-1","type":"Annotation","motivation":"painting","target":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04918/canvas/1","body":{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04918/tiles/full/1920,1080/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":1080,"width":1920,"service":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04918/tiles","type":"ImageService3","profile":"http://iiif.io/api/image/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04918/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04918/canvas/1/40ede7e3-ce79-4af4-a6f2-c4dcfbfa3808","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-29T19:29:01.723Z","creator":"Tallulah Stallvik","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>One persistent question in the response to <em>Phantom Thread </em>was whether it challenges or condones toxic masculinity. Owen Gleiberman, for example, called the film a “parable of toxic masculinity” (“<a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" class=\"Hyperlink SCXW184301983 BCX0\" href=\"https://variety.com/2017/film/reviews/phantom-thread-review-daniel-day-lewis-1202632204/\"><u>Film Review</u></a>”) while Aleksandar Hemon wrote that critics failed to see in it “a symptom of the Weinsteinian toxic masculinity exposed by the #MeToo movement” (“<a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" class=\"Hyperlink SCXW184301983 BCX0\" href=\"https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/why-phantom-thread-is-propaganda-for-toxic-masculinity\"><u>Why </u><em><u>Phantom Thread</u></em><u> Is Propaganda</u></a>”). In general, these critics see Alma as consistently subservient to Reynolds, even when she begins poisoning him, as her entire world revolves around him, and she struggles to remain within the House of Woodcock. A counterargument, one that doesn’t even deny the elements of toxic masculinity essential to Reynolds’s personality and behavior, might point out that <em>she</em> is the one who tells the entire story of the film, as show in the bookend scenes, a narrative move that grants her an agency that Reynolds lacks. The response to Gleiberman’s review was so intensive that it prompted him to issue another piece, “<a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" class=\"Hyperlink SCXW184301983 BCX0\" href=\"https://variety.com/2018/film/columns/phantom-thread-is-about-toxic-masculinity-daniel-day-lewis-1202654772\"><u>The Twisted Fascination of ‘Phantom Thread’: If This Isn’t Toxic Masculinity, What Is?</u></a>” A summary of these takes can be found in Rochelle Siemienowicz’s “<a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" class=\"Hyperlink SCXW184301983 BCX0\" href=\"https://www.sbs.com.au/whats-on/article/a-guide-to-the-worst-takes-on-phantom-thread/uvioeee30\"><u>A guide to the worst takes on 'Phantom Thread'</u></a>.” See also Guy Lodge’s “<a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" class=\"Hyperlink SCXW184301983 BCX0\" href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/jan/02/how-phantom-thread-undresses-our-ideas-about-toxic-masculinity\"><u>How Phantom Thread undresses our ideas about toxic masculinity</u></a>.”&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-04918/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:19.96707375081794,18.69848025376239,269.92245199409166,246.7134416543575"}}}]}]}]}